Endow S with the pinning \lambda associated to \mathcal{O}\_{\operatorname{Spec}\mathbf{Z}} (Example 3.1.5), and let M be an R-linear MW-module over S.
   We say that M satisfies the property \big{(}\text{FT}^{R}\_{X}\big{)} for an S-scheme X of finite type (resp. satisfies the property \big{(}\text{FT}^{R}\big{)}) if \operatorname{\mathcal{D}}\_{\lambda}(M) does so.

###### Remark 4.5.4.

1. (1)

   If one uses induction on the dimension and the localization sequence 1.5.8,
   property \big{(}\text{FT}^{R}\big{)} can be reduced to \big{(}\text{FT}^{R}\_{X}\big{)} for finite type regular affine schemes X over \mathbf{Z}.
2. (2)

   The property \big{(}\text{FT}^{\mathbf{Z}}\big{)} implies \big{(}\text{FT}^{R}\big{)} for any noetherian ring R, by the Universal Coefficient Theorem.
3. (3)

   For the classical MW-(ho)modules (namely the ones enlisted in Conjecture 4.5.5 below), one should not expect the homological finiteness to hold over general schemes.
   For example, for an infinite field k one has A\_{0}(k,\operatorname{K}^{M}\_{1})=k^{\*} which is not a finitely generated abelian group.
   Instead, this property incarnates an arithmetic finiteness property, which is expected to hold for arithmetic schemes such as number rings or finite fields,
   and in practice one should restrict to schemes of finite type over \operatorname{Spec}\mathbf{Z}.
   However, it is useful to have some flexibility, as in Definition 4.5.3.
4. (4)

   The properties \big{(}\text{FT}^{R}\_{X}\big{)} and \big{(}\text{FT}^{R}\big{)} do not depend on the underlying choice of the dimension function \delta on S.
   In the case of MW-modules, these properties are independent of the choice of pinning, if one only considers pinnings associated to dualizing complexes (Example 3.1.5).

We conjecture the following arithmetic finiteness property for some usual MW-modules:

###### Conjecture 4.5.5.

The MW-modules \operatorname{K}^{MW}\_{\*}, \operatorname{K}^{M}\_{\*}, I^{\*}, \mathcal{GW}\_{\*}, \mathcal{W}\_{\*} and \mathcal{K}\_{\*} over \operatorname{Spec}\mathbf{Z}
(see Examples  1.3.6, 3.3.6,3.5.6 and 4.3.3) satisfy the property \big{(}\text{FT}^{\mathbf{Z}}\big{)}.

###### Remark 4.5.6.

1. (1)

   Note that the MW-module \mathcal{K}\_{\*} is only partially related to \operatorname{K}^{M}\_{\*}:
   the associated Milnor cycle modules
   over \mathbf{Z} coincide only up to degree 3. Nonetheless, this coincidence is sufficient
   to ensure that both cycle modules define the *same* Chow groups. In particular,
   the property \big{(}\text{FT}^{\mathbf{Z}}\big{)} for any of the two would imply that Chow groups of
   finite type \mathbf{Z}-schemes are finitely generated abelian groups.
2. (2)

   The MW-homodule \mathcal{GW}\_{\*} satisfies \big{(}\text{FT}^{R}\_{X}\big{)} if both MW-homodules \mathcal{K}\_{\*} and \mathcal{W}\_{\*} satisfy \big{(}\text{FT}^{R}\_{X}\big{)}. By the short exact sequence (3.4.5.b), the MW-module \operatorname{K}^{MW}\_{\*} satisfies \big{(}\text{FT}^{R}\_{X}\big{)} if both MW-modules \operatorname{K}^{M}\_{\*} and \operatorname{I}^{\*} satisfy \big{(}\text{FT}^{R}\_{X}\big{)}.
3. (3)

   Since \operatorname{W}\_{\*}[1/2]\simeq\operatorname{I}^{\*}[1/2], the property \big{(}\text{FT}^{\mathbb{Z}[1/2]}\big{)} for these two MW-modules are equivalent after inverting 2. We will actually prove this property later in Proposition 4.5.14.

